\c 3
\v 1 In his eighteenth year Nebuchadnezzar the king made an image of gold. Its height was sixty cubits, and its breadth six cubits. He set it up in the plain of Dura, in the land of Babylon.
\v 2 And he sent out invitations to all the governors and generals and magistrates and chiefs and princes and all those in authority and all the rulers of countries to come to the dedication of the image.
\v 3 Then the magistrates and governors and generals and chiefs and great princes and those in authority and all the governors of countries gathered together for the dedication of the image which Nebuchadnezzar the king had set up.
\v 4 Then a herald cried aloud, “To you peoples and nations and tribes and languages it is commanded
\v 5 that whenever you hear the sound of the trumpet and pipe and harp and sackbut and psaltery and and every kind of music that you fall down and worship the golden image which king Nebuchadnezzar has set up.
\v 6 And whoever does not fall down and worship at that time shall be thrown into the burning fiery furnace.”
\v 7 And so it was that when the nations heard the sound of the trumpet and pipe and harp and sackbut and psaltery and every kind of music all the nations and tribes and languages fell down and worshipped the golden image which king Nebuchadnezzar had set up.
\v 8 Then certain Chaldeans approached the king and accused the Jews, saying,
\v 9 “O king, live for ever.
\v 10 You, O king, have made a decree that everyone who hears the sound of the trumpet and pipe and harp and sackbut and psaltery and and all kinds of music,
\v 11 and does not fall down and worship the golden image, shall be thrown into the burning fiery furnace.
\v 12 There are certain Jews whom you have set over the affairs of the land of Babylon, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, who have not obeyed your decree, O king. They do not serve your gods, nor worship the golden image which you have set up.”
\v 13 Then Nebuchadnezzar in his rage and fury commanded Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego to be brought; and they were brought before the king.
\v 14 And Nebuchadnezzar demanded of them, “Is it true, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, that you do not serve my gods, nor worship the golden image which I have set up?
\v 15 Now then, if you are ready whenever you hear the sound of trumpet and pipe and harp and sackbut and psaltery and and every kind of music to fall down and worship the golden image which I have set up, that is well. But if you do not worship at that time, you shall be thrown into the burning fiery furnace; and who is the God who can deliver you out of my hands?”
\v 16 Then Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego answered and said to king Nebuchadnezzar, “We have no need to answer you concerning this matter,
\v 17 for our God whom we serve is in the heavens, and able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace, and he will rescue us out of your hands, O king.
\v 18 But if not, let it be known to you, O king, that we will not serve your gods nor worship the golden image which you have set up.”
\v 19 Then Nebuchadnezzar was full of fury, and his face glowered at Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego. He commanded the furnace to be heated seven times hotter, until it should burn to the uttermost.
\v 20 And he commanded strong men to bind Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, and to throw them into the burning fiery furnace.
\v 21 Then those men were bound in their coats and caps and stockings and other clothes, and they were thrown into the middle of the burning fiery furnace.
\v 22 The king’s word prevailed and the furnace was made extremely hot.
\v 23 These three men, Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, fell bound into the middle of the burning furnace,
\v 24 and walked about in the middle of the flames, singing praises to God, and blessing the Lord.
\s The Prayer of Azarias
\p
\v 25 Azarias prayed like this, and opening his mouth in the midst of the fire, he said,
\q1
\v 26 “Blessed are you, Lord God of our fathers: and praised and glorified is your name unto the ages.
\q1
\v 27 For you are righteous in all the things that you have done to us: and all your works are true, all your ways are right, and all your judgements are just.
\q1
\v 28 And in all the things that you have brought upon us, and upon the holy city of our fathers, even Jerusalem, you have executed true judgement: for in accordance with truth and justice you brought all these things upon us because of our sins.
\q1
\v 29 For we have sinned and committed iniquity, turning away from you,
\v 30 and in all things we have trespassed, and not obeyed your laws, nor kept them, nor done as you have commanded us, that it might go well with us.
\q1
\v 31 Therefore all that you have brought upon us, and everything you have done to us, you have done with justice.
\q1
\v 32 And you delivered us into the hands of our lawless enemies, and to an unjust king, the most wicked in all the world.
\q1
\v 33 And now we cannot open our mouths, we have become a cause of shame and reproach to your servants, and to those who honour you.
\q1
\v 34 Yet do not wholly abandon us for your name’s sake, nor cancel your covenant:
\q1
\v 35 and do not let your mercy leave us, for your beloved Abraham’s sake, and for your servant Isaac’s sake, and for your holy Israel’s sake.
\q1
\v 36 To these you have spoken and promised that you would multiply their descendants like the stars of heaven, and like the sand which lies on the sea shore.
\q1
\v 37 For we, Lord, have become less than all the nations, and are now humbled in all the world because of our sins.
\q1
\v 38 Nor is there at this time any prince or prophet or leader or burnt offering or sacrifice or oblation or incense or place to sacrifice before you so that we might find mercy.
\q1
\v 39 Nevertheless with a contrite heart and humble spirit let us be accepted:
\v 40 like burnt offerings of rams and bullocks, of ten thousand fat lambs, so let our sacrifice be acceptable in your sight this day.
\q1 Let it be accepted for those who follow you: for there is no shame for those who put their trust in you.
\q1
\v 41 And now we follow you with all our heart, and we fear you, and seek your face.
\q1
\v 42 Do not put us to shame: but deal with us according to your loving-kindness, and according to the multitude of your mercies.
\q1
\v 43 Deliver us also by your marvellous works, and give glory to your name, Lord: and let all those who harm your servants be put to shame;
\v 44 and let all their power and might be confounded, and let their strength be broken.
\q1
\v 45 Let them know that you alone, Lord, are God, and glorious over the whole world.”
\p
\v 46 Now the king’s servants who had thrown them in, stopped stoking furnace with naphtha and pitch and tow and kindling.
\v 47 The flames leapt up above the furnace forty-nine cubits,
\v 48 and the fire broke through and burned those Chaldeans it found around the furnace.
\v 49 But the angel of the Lord came down into the furnace to join Azarias and his companions. He quenched the flames of the fire within of the furnace,
\v 50 and made the inside of the furnace as if a moist breeze were blowing through it; so the fire did not touch them at all, nor hurt or trouble them.
